  <note>
    <title>PNL 2015</title>
    <created>19691215T142607Z</created>
    <updated>20141223T082036Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>sslooten</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note style="word-wrap: break-word; -webkit-nbsp-mode: space; -webkit-line-break: after-white-space;">

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">2015</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Every software company needs to continuously reinvent itself. In fact, it’s not only software companies that face this problem, car manufactures who would still produce horse carriages, would be out of business. The only difference is that we tend to move faster.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Prisma IT has always done this by scouting the market, finding an opportunity (programming language or other), start to work with it, start delivering training, find customers who wanted software build with these tools and then adapt in the organization. This was the case with ColdFusion, Flex, LiveCycle, Mura, frameworks etc.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">The reason why we have always succeeded is that there would always be one person, who would be the “evangelist” of the new language. For CF &amp; Flex that person was me, for LiveCycle it was Jochem, for frameworks Mark would often be an evangelist. Ron for Brightcove and for Mura it is Guust.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">In the last few years we have not really been able to re-invent ourselves on a continuous basis. And that is starting to worry me more and more.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">There is an old saying: “if you don’t rewrite your code, someone else will do it for you”. </span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">I believe we have been in the danger zone of “falling behind” for the last 2 or 3 years.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">In the last few years, we have tried to adapt new technologies, but - apart from Mura and Brightcove - we havent really been able to do so. And having said that, I believe Mura and Brightcove aren’t the ones that will be able to “make the difference”. They are nice, but they will not be the big differentiators to get us into and through 2015 and further.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Mendix, AWS training, BonitaSoft, DataLogics, DocOrigin are all technologies that we have not been able to adapt to and, as a result, we let them slip.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div>If Prisma IT wants to survive and lead in this continuously faster moving world, we need to change our model and adapt faster and with more conviction to changes and new oportunities.</div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">For the next years, We need to have a discussion and build a plan around the idea to become a “Cloud Architected Software” centric company.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">What I have seen in the last few days from AWS blew my mind. for the first time in over 14 years and for the 5th time in my career, I believe we found something that can help us push ourselves to the next stage. After DEC VAX, Apple Macintosh, ColdFusion and Flex, I believe Cloud centric (or cloud architected) *we need to find a better term* development will completely change the paradigm of software development.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Our partner of choice is AWS.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Over the last couple of years, AWS has been handled by us on the level of system management. We build applications, hand them over to sysmngmnt and they deploy. Either on our own hardware or in the cloud.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">We need to rapidly change this model. “Cloud awareness” needs to become cloud architected and needs to be handled at the architect level. We need to start designing and architecting our applications (projects, existing projects and repeatable solutions) around the possibilities that AWS provides.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">We also (and at the same time) need to change the way we develop. AWS tools like AWS CodeCommit, CodeDeploy CodePipeline, AWS Container Service, Docker and Apollo all need to be at the heart of our development methodologies.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Running the apps we build on AWS will be the standard.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Technologies like AWS Lambda will fundamentally change the way we build software.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">At the same time we need to start projects and programs with sales and marketing to start talking to customers, add content on our website etc.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">We need to come up with a way to be able to adapt to new technologies and features that AWS releases. Just as an indication of the speed they are approbating: AWS has released more than 500 new technologies and features since Jan 1 2014!</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">And the scary thing is that they build up even more speed with their releases.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">This will be a huge project for 2015 and it will mean that everybody needs to commit to this.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">We need to do this. It will be hard work and fun and it will make us better.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><span style="font-family: Calibri; font-size: 14px;">I have created this text as the start of an internal discussion with management, team leads, developers and sysmngmnt on how to do this.</span><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><span style="font-family: Calibri; font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></div>

	
	
	
	<div><span style="font-family: Calibri; font-size: 14px;">We can not afford to miss this one and we cannot afford to wait another year.</span></div>

	
	
	
	<div><span style="font-family: Calibri; font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></div>

	
	
	
	<div><span style="font-family: Calibri; font-size: 14px;">Prisma IT needs to expand in 5 different focus areas in 2015</span></div>

	
	
	
	<div><span style="font-family: Calibri; font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></div>

	
	
	
	<div><span style="font-family: Calibri; font-size: 14px;">- Revenues for PNL need to go up by 30% to 2.6MM</span></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- The Alliant Solution Suite needs to be finalised and launched</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- We need to expand out international operations into different regions</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- We need to expand our solutions &amp; services offering with (at least) mobile &amp; Search optimalisation services (SEO, SEA etc)</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- We need to make AWS the core of our software Dev &amp; Ops work. AWS needs to be included at the architectural level of what we do</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">Further, we must complete a number of internal projects:</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Single Signon for all Prisma IT services (Through PingONe?)</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Pass out of international servers</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Move Domain controllers to the cloud</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Move all backups to the cloud</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Move Fileshares to the cloud (Sharepoint, Zocalo or other?)</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Move dev environments (of non-standard environments) to EC2?</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Update &amp; Professionalize WIFI at HQ</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Setup a Prisma IT blog</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- Make sure new clients/projects/releases are on our website on the day of the release</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">- </span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;">And we need to create a m eeting scheme that works for everybody.</span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></div>

	
	
	
	<div>

		
		
		
		<hr/>
<font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"> </span></font>
	
	
	
	</div>

	
	
	
	<div><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><font face="Calibri"><span style="font-size: 14px;"><br/></span></font></span></font></div>
