[17/10/14 15:00:09] Malcolm O'Keeffe: Just talked to gert - short call, but positive reaction to:

	
	
	<div>[17/10/14 15:00:33] Malcolm O'Keeffe: 1. Providing you and Calle review of his slides prior to CF Camp , and promise to not “go off script”</div>

	
	
	<div>[17/10/14 15:01:06] Malcolm O'Keeffe: 2. The concepts that you and I came up with today. Here’s the email I wrote him:</div>

	
	
	<div>[17/10/14 15:03:10] Malcolm O'Keeffe: The compromise we discussed returns close to the original concepts of TRC, but with some significant changes. The basic plan would be for TRC to release a Commercial and Open Source version of Railo 5, and for TRC to pursue the commercial activities and opportunities for Railo Server.</div>

	
	
	<div><br/></div>

	
	
	<div>Here’s what’s significantly different from the first TRC arrangement:</div>

	
	
	<div>RT has much more freedom than under original agreement</div>

	
	
	<div>RT is not employed by TRC, but is paid on a per-hour worked agreement</div>

	
	
	<div>Calle to represent 4F in TRC, no direct Simon involvement</div>

	
	
	<div>TRC is run with maximum focus on transparency, profit. No secrets, total visibility for all shareholders.</div>

	
	
	<div>New accountant and accounting system to provide all shareholders more confidence and information.</div>

	
	
	<div>Sales compensation is mostly (maybe all) commission-based (no big salaries)</div>

	
	
	<div>All current contracts between TRC and shareholders (RT, 4F, BR) are reviewed and updated with much more precise legal guidance and clarity</div>

	
	
	<div><br/></div>

	
	
	<div>What stays the same:</div>

	
	
	<div><br/></div>

	
	
	<div>TRC owns the IP</div>

	
	
	<div>TRC releases an open source Railo Server (full featured, but with slower release cycle to encourage commercial server sales)</div>

	
	
	<div>TRC releases a commercial Railo Server (initially using old method of authentication - <a href="http://Railo.IO">Railo.IO</a> maybe introduced later)</div>

	
	
	<div>RT, BR and 4F keep active input via Board of Directors</div>

	
	
	<div>TRC exclusive licensor of paid support, paid training, server-specific consulting (performance tuning, bug fixes, etc.)</div>

	
	
	<div><br/></div>

	
	
	<div>What (I think) is good for RT about this concept:</div>

	
	
	<div>Prevents expensive and time consuming legal battle</div>

	
	
	<div>Provides RT with a significant increase in autonomy and freedom</div>

	
	
	<div>RT leads development and release cycle of Railo Server (with TRC feedback and input on RT plans).</div>

	
	
	<div><b>—> TRC always needs to give final approval, also subject to TDAC’s role</b></div>

	
	
	<div>Eliminates uncertainty: RT free of legal complications or threats</div>

	
	
	<div>Gert and Michael retain community position as Railo core team</div>

	
	
	<div>RT free to pursue any other commercial activities (only restricted on TRC specific stuff like paid support, paid training, server-specific consulting) - RT can pursue web and application development that uses Railo, Java tools, etc.</div>

	
	
	<div>RT can choose to either retain ownership of Railo Tools or get paid for this work and “sell” them to TRC</div>

	
	
	<div><b>—> TRC has paid a number of months “salary” while they said they were working on these products. A certain percentage of the products (subject to further discussion) is already owned by TRC. This will not be just “their choice"</b></div>

	
	
	<div>RT retains its shares in TRC, commission structure (15% of net profits annually, etc)</div>

	
	
	<div><br/></div>

	
	
	<div>Miscellaneous notes:</div>

	
	
	<div>Both 4F and RT can offer commercial add-ons to Railo Commercial Server to increase value - must be agreed upon by all before included in offering. Revenue sharing arrangements for any contributions to be worked out prior to inclusion.</div>

	
	
	<div>TRC will get early access to bug/security fixes for inclusion in commercial server, before release in open source server</div>

	
	
	<div><b>--> since everything is owned by TRC, I don’t “get” this.</b></div>

	
	
	<div>TRC can count on RT to maintain compatibility with Morpheus and other 4F products</div>

	
	
	<div><b>—> TRC has final decision on what is done to the product, so this is good, but not really necessary</b></div>

	
	
	<div>There will not be any further legal actions from both sides, neither against 4FTi nor Simon Slooten nor Gert Franz, etc.</div>

	
	
	<div>The matter of the 3% commission still to be addressed</div>

	
	
	<div><b>—> All financials still need to be addressed. A balance sheet needs to be created. there will be amounts on the left side and on the right side of the balance</b></div>

	
	
	<div>The work performed to date during 2014 by RT that benefits TRC to be compensated - arrangement to be discussed and negotiated</div>

	
	
	<div><b>—> In relation to amounts invoiced by RT to “Swiss customers"</b></div>

	
	
	<div>The “financial audit” proposed by Blue River can move forward, and financial negotiations can follow based on findings, OR all sides can call for a fresh start from today. Whether this potential “fresh start” includes the 3% commission is not yet decided.</div>

	
	
	<div><b>—> A “fresh start” would include everything</b></div>

	
	
	<div>[17/10/14 15:05:36] Malcolm O'Keeffe: If there’s content in there that’s different from your recollection please let me know soon so we catch any inaccuracies early</div>



	
